# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2-park-avenue
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] It is 632 feet (193 m) high, with 48 floors, and contains 350,000 sq ft (33,000 m2) of office or mixed-use space.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] It was previously known as the Chase Tower, after its first tenant, Chase Brass & Copper.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] Its owner until his death in 1938 was Frederick William Vanderbilt.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] During the 1970s, the building housed part of the Mid-Manhattan Library.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] In September 2002, the building's lobby was renovated, restoring the 15-foot (4.6 m) ceilings.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] Current tenants include the Moroccan consulate.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] On November 14, 2007, the building became the final site to be removed from Thomas Edison's original direct current grid in New York City.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] The building was completed in 1929 when 90 percent of the electricity in lower Manhattan was direct current.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] In that year New York Edison announced plans that it was going to convert the entire system to alternating current.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] The last 2 rotary converter substations generating direct current (at West 26th and West 39th Street) were retired in 1977 and the DC conversions were handled by solid-state rectifier units.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] The 2007 event shifted the responsibility for providing the conversion from Con Edison to the building via a local converter.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] Many of the buildings built in 1929 and before still use direct current with the local converter – most notably for elevators.
[src:2-park-avenue/10-east-40th-street] The New York City Subway's third rail electric system is still direct current (with the Metropolitan Transportation Authority providing the local converters from AC to DC.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The building is at the southwest corner of Sixth Avenue (Avenue of the Americas) and West 37th Street in the Garment District of Midtown Manhattan, New York City.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The nearly rectangular land lot covers 8,041 square feet (747.0 m2), with a frontage of 98.75 feet (30.10 m) on Sixth Avenue and a depth of 100 feet (30 m); there is a rectangular cutout at the lot's northwest corner.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] Immediately to the south is the Greenwich Savings Bank Building, while Bryant Park and the New York Public Library Main Branch are a few blocks north.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] Casoni was designed by the architectural firm C3D Architecture for clients Sioni Group and RPY 989 LLC.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The tower will be 743 feet (226 m) tall and have 68 floors.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The building's form is divided into four sections.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The lowermost section is a cylindrical, glass-clad mass that is similar in height to the Greenwich Savings Bank Building.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The upper stories are clad with metal and glass, with balconies facing northeast toward the intersection of 37th Street and Sixth Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] Inside are 311 residential condominiums, each spanning 991 square feet (92.1 m2) on average.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The smallest apartments are studio apartments, while the largest units have three bedrooms.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] There are also 86,817 square feet (8,065.6 m2) set aside for commercial uses and an amenity space spanning 25,000 square feet (2,300 m2) across two floors.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The 23rd floor, 58th floor, and roof have exterior terraces.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] To maximize usable space, the building's structural core is located on the western boundary of the site, near the middle of the city block.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The site previously contained two structures—a one-story building at 993 Sixth Avenue and an adjacent 21-story building at 989–991 Sixth Avenue—owned by real-estate investors Isaac Chetrit of the Chetrit Group and Ray Yadidi of the Sioni Group.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] They had paid $49 million for 989–991 Sixth Avenue in 2007.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The partners further paid $54.3 million in 2015 for 993 Sixth Avenue, which at the time was planned to be replaced with a hotel.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The same year, they bought the air rights above the adjacent Greenwich Savings Bank Building.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] Chetrit and Yadidi were theoretically allowed to build a skyscraper of up to 80 stories and 375,000 square feet (34,800 m2) of space.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] Chetrit hired Kohn Pedersen Fox to design the tower in 2017.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] Simultaneously, Chetrit was considering selling the site, even though the developers were already demolishing 993 Sixth Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] In December 2021, Chetrit and Yadidi submitted plans to the New York City Department of Buildings to develop a 68-story building at 989–993 Sixth Avenue, to be designed by architect of record C3D Architecture.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The next year, the Sioni Group negotiated to borrow $350 million to build the skyscraper.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] At the time, Sioni was preparing to demolish the building at 989–991 Sixth Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] However, it was unable to receive financing from traditional banks due to high interest rates.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] In 2023, Sioni borrowed $47 million for the building's construction from Valley National Bank.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] Renderings for the tower were released that August, and the site had been cleared by November.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] By summer 2024, the two basement levels were constructed and construction of the ground floor began.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] The building had reached the height of the neighboring high-rise buildings by the end of the year.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] Work had reached 25 stories in January 2025, and the structure had been built to half its final height by that March.
[src:2-park-avenue/100-west-37th-street] In April 2025, Sion received a $275 million construction loan for the project, and the firm hired Real New York as the building's brokerage.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] The building is currently a co-op owned by its residents.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] Among the former residents of the building are the British author P.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] Rorimer, former Director of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, and Nicola Kraus, co-author of the 2002 bestselling chick lit novel *The Nanny Diaries*.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] X, the mother in the novel, set at a similar Park Avenue building with a fictitious address, is based partially on women she worked for at 1000 Park.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] Most often speculated as the model for the character is Lisa Birnbach, a part-time CBS News correspondent best known for editing *The Official Preppy Handbook* in 1980, who has some similarities to the character in the book.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] Birnbach confirmed that Kraus had worked for her, but described her as "more of a play date for my daughter" than an actual nanny.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] Another resident of 1000 Park named as a possible model for Mrs.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] X did not return phone calls from *The New York Times* requesting comment.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] Kraus did not think it inappropriate to use her former neighbors as models for her characters, but current residents of building disagreed.
[src:2-park-avenue/1000-park-avenue] One even referred to Kraus as a "snitch" and suggested the co-op board should forbid residents from fictionalizing their neighbors' lives.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] It features in the 1983 film Escape from the Bronx as President Clark's headquarters of the General Construction (GC) Corporation.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] It was used as the facade of the fictional "Pemrose building" in the 1987 film *The Secret of My Success*, as well as the fictional "Clamp Center" in the 1990 film *Gremlins 2: The New Batch*.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] The building features in the 1991 Jeff Bridges film *The Fisher King*, and is shown as the site of George Costanza's office in a few ninth-season episodes of *Seinfeld*, as well as Dudley Moore's character's office in the film *Crazy People*.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] *Person of Interest* used the building several times including as IFT Headquarters in season one.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] The rooftop of the building was featured in the 2011 film *Friends with Benefits*.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] The building is featured as a crash site in the 2012 film *The Avengers*.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] It was used for a brief exit shot in the 2012 Richard Gere film *Arbitrage*.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] Most recently, it was featured as the office in the 2019 film *Isn't It Romantic*.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] The building's roof was used in the 1985 second season feature length opener of Miami Vice, where Crockett & Tubbs face a showdown with an NYPD hostile to their investigation into a powerful Colombian drug dealing syndicate operating in the city.
[src:2-park-avenue/101-park-avenue] It is also on the roof of this skyscraper that the final shots of the clip made for the piece *Looking up*, by Michel Petrucciani, were shot.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] From 2006 to 2007, the tower was upgraded from Class B+ to Class A office space for $260 million.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] The phone company moved its headquarters to 140 West Street in the early 2000s and sold off most of the Sixth Avenue building.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] Verizon retained a condominium interest in floors 6-12, where it maintained offices and a telephone exchange serving landlines in Midtown Manhattan.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] In 2013, the company moved its corporate headquarters back to 1095 Avenue of the Americas after selling the upper floors of the Verizon Building.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] In 2015, Ivanhoé Cambridge and Callahan Capital Properties purchased 1095 Avenue of the Americas from The Blackstone Group for $2.2 billion, the most expensive transaction involving a single office building in New York City since 2008.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] In August 2016, Real Summit Investment, a real estate investment subsidiary of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority's Exchange Fund, paid $1.15 billion for a 49% stake in the building.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] In addition to Verizon, other major tenants as of late 2008 include insurance giant MetLife (whose name is outside above the entryway), law firm Dechert LLP, iStar Financial, Lloyds Banking Group, Instinet, Standard Chartered USA, and Stifel.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] In 2013, Whole Foods Market finalized a deal to open a 32,000-square-foot (3,000 m2) flagship location spread across the first and second floors of the building.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] The market opened its doors in January 2017.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] Pandora Jewelry, Tourneau, and Equinox Fitness also operate in the base of the building.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] ASICS abruptly vacated its 5,000-square-foot (460 m2) space in October 2015 amid a legal battle with the company's retail operator, less than a year after moving in.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] In 2016, Salesforce signed a deal to rename the building Salesforce Tower, and the San Francisco-based company plans to eventually occupy 5 floors.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] The first Salesforce employees in New York City to move to the new office arrived on Monday November 14, 2016.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] Bancorp signed a lease for 68,000 square feet (6,300 m2) in September 2016 and Apollo Global Management followed in July 2017 with a 70,000 square feet (6,500 m2) lease.
[src:2-park-avenue/1095-avenue-of-the-americas] Lloyds Bank leased approximately 35,000 square feet (3,300 m2) in January 2019, bringing the building to 96% occupancy.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] As it was not a freestanding structure, 110 East 42nd Street deviated from traditional bank building designs, being laid out as an office building with a bank.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The sandstone facade is divided into three vertical sections: the base, tower, and upper stories.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Within the four-story base on 42nd Street, there is a small office entrance to the west, a large round-arched entrance at the center, and a smaller arcade to the east.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The remainder of the facade is split by vertical piers into multiple bays.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The ground floor contains an 80-by-197.5-foot (24.4 by 60.2 m) rectangular room behind the arch, stretching 65 feet (20 m) tall; this was originally the banking room.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] An annex known as the "Chapel" is to the east of the banking room, and an elevator vestibule and subway entrance are to the west.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] 110 East 42nd Street, as well as the adjacent Pershing Square Building, were built on the site of the Grand Union Hotel.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Construction started in 1921 and was completed in 1923, and an addition was built between 1931 and 1933.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Its facade and banking hall were made New York City designated landmarks in 1996.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The building was sold to SL Green in 1998, and the former banking space was turned into an event venue and banquet hall operated by Cipriani S.A.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The upper floors of 110 East 42nd Street continue to be used as an office building.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Gotham Realty owned the office floors from 2007 to 2011, and Meadow Partners took ownership of the office stories in December 2021.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] 110 East 42nd Street is in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] It is bounded by 42nd Street to the north and 41st Street to the south, in the middle of the city block between Park Avenue to the west and Lexington Avenue to the east.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] On the same block, the Pershing Square Building is to the west and the Chanin Building is to the east.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Other nearby buildings include the Grand Hyatt New York hotel to the north, the Chrysler Building to the northeast, the Socony-Mobil Building to the east, and 101 Park Avenue to the south.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The completion of the underground Grand Central Terminal in 1913 resulted in the rapid development of Terminal City, the area around Grand Central, as well as a corresponding increase in real-estate prices.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Among these were the New York Central Building at 47th Street and Park Avenue, as well as the Grand Central Palace across 42nd Street from the present 110 East 42nd Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] By 1920, the area had become what *The New York Times* called "a great civic centre".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The building was designed in the Italian Romanesque Revival style by the firm of York & Sawyer.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The design shares many elements with the Pershing Square Building directly to the west, which was also co-designed by York & Sawyer.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Fuller Company was the general contractor, and numerous other contractors and material suppliers were involved in the building's construction.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] *Architecture and Building* characterized the building as having been inspired by Byzantine architecture, while architect and writer Robert A.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Stern described the edifice as containing elements of both the Byzantine and the Romanesque.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] York and Sawyer's original plans for 110 East 42nd Street called for a four-story-tall banking room, topped by thirteen office floors, to extend the width of the block between 41st and 42nd Streets.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A hip-roofed penthouse on top of the office floors would bring the building's height to 18 floors.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The building has a frontage of 104 feet (32 m) on 42nd Street and extends 198 feet (60 m) to the back of the lot at 41st Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] As it was not a freestanding structure, 110 East 42nd Street deviated from traditional bank building designs, including that of the original main branch at Bowery and Grand Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Most significantly, it did not resemble a "modified Greek temple" as earlier bank buildings had.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The building was instead designed in the Italian Romanesque Revival style, The Italian Romanesque design provided consistency to the facade, since the Pershing Square Building to the west was designed in a similar manner.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] York & Sawyer's ultimate design emphasized the juxtaposition of office and banking concerns in the building, which are stacked one above the other.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The placement of offices above the banking hall reflected the limitations of the small site.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The facade is divided into three vertical sections: the base, tower, and upper stories.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The facade contains elements such as arcades, and cornices with corbelling.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A variety of materials and colors are used for the building's individual elements.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The facade elements are also decorated with representations of figures such as "birds, beasts, fantastic mythological creatures [and] human forms".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The 42nd Street facade is largely made of Ohio sandstone.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] On the 42nd Street side, there are also columns and colonettes made of pink granite; tiled wall copings; and spandrels made of green marble.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The spandrels separate metal-framed windows on each story.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The 41st Street facade is made of sandstone on the first floor, and buff-colored bonded brick above it.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] At the bottom of both facades is a water table made of granite, which is 3 feet (0.91 m) higher on the eastern part of the building, due to the area's topography sloping downward to the east.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Allegorical decorations, attributed to the firm of Ricci and Zari, are also placed on the facade.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] On the four-story base facing 42nd Street to the north, there is a large round-arched entrance taking up most of the facade, with detailed archivolts running on the underside of the archway.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The arch measures 27 feet (8.2 m) wide and 47 feet (14 m) high.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The large ground-floor arch leads to the giant banking room inside.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A short flight of stairs leads to a set of doors, above which is a large window that fills the rest of the arch opening.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] There are voussoirs running along the top of the arch, with a carved motif located within every other voussoir.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A pair of rose windows, small circular apertures, are located at the fourth floor flanking the top of the arch.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] An arcade with arched openings runs along the fifth floor facade.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Also above this large arch are carvings of numerous animals that represent facets of the savings industry.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] These include a squirrel, a rooster, a dog, a lion, an owl, an eagle, a human with keys, and a farmer.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] To the west of the main archway (on the right side as seen from 42nd Street), a small arch provides access to the office tower's entrance vestibule, the elevator lobby, and the Grand Central–42nd Street subway station.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The entrance contains a semicircular tympanum above the doorway, with a geometric pattern, as well as embossed surrounds on either side of the doorway.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The words "The Bowery Savings Bank Building" are inscribed on top of the tympanum, and the building's address is fully spelled out on the bottom of the tympanum.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Above this archway are two pairs of windows, one each at the third and fourth floors.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The third floor includes two rectangular windows and the fourth floor contains two arched grilles in place of window openings.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] To the east (left) is the six-story "Chapel" annex completed in 1933.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The lower two floors contain a three-arched arcade with two granite columns.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The rectangular third-floor windows and arched fourth-floor windows are similar to those on the west side of the facade.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Above the first- and second-floor arcade, there are four carved motifs, located at even intervals, as well as an inscription "A Mutual Institution Chartered 1834 To Serve Those Who Save".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] There is an arcade running across the 5th story facade.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The facade of the base on 41st Street, to the south, is similar in that it also contains a large archivolted arch with a set of doors below a large window.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] However, the doors on the 41st Street facade are located in a three-faced structure that projects slightly.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The entrance arch on 41st Street is the same size as that on 42nd Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Flanking the arch are three bays, two to the west (left) and one to the east (right) of the arch.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] These bays each contain two rectangular windows on the second floor, two arched windows on the third floor, and a rose window on the fourth floor.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A driveway leading to an underground parking garage is located on the first floor underneath the leftmost bay.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The upper floors are largely finished in limestone with marble spandrels and metal-framed windows.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] On the 42nd Street side above the four-story base, the 5th through 13th floors are articulated with vertical piers and window spandrels.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The piers divide the facade into five bays: four above the main banking entrance in the center, and one bay above the office-building entrance on the west (right) side.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Each bay contains two windows on each floor.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Horizontal cornices with corbeling are located above the 14th and 17th floors.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] There is an arcade running across the 5th story facade, as well as another arcade running across the 15th and 16th stories.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The 17th story contains round-arched window openings while the 18th story consists of four windows that each contain three panes.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] On the 17th floor, at the top of 110 East 42nd Street's tower section, are tiled copings.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] At the 42nd Street facade, a flagpole extends from the center of the tower section at the fifth floor, directly above the center of the archway.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] On the 41st Street side, the facade rises nine stories from ground level, with a cornice at the top of this section.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Above the ninth floor, the building contains a 22-foot (6.7 m) setback, and the tower rises behind this setback to the 17th story.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The 41st Street side is also articulated with vertical piers and window spandrels.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] It also contains five bays, with each bay containing two windows per floor.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The first floor consists of three sections: an elevator vestibule on the west, a banking room on the center, and the smaller "Chapel" section to the east.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The annex and banking rooms use a mixture of materials on the walls and columns.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] According to the Landmarks Preservation Commission, these include ashlar as well as "marble, limestone, sandstone, imitation stone, and plaster".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Valuables were stored in a bank vault in the basement, measuring 9 feet 8 inches (2.95 m) wide and 36 feet (11 m) deep.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The York Safe and Lock Company built a rectangular steel vault door measuring 36 inches (910 mm) thick.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The banking room uses marble, limestone, sandstone and bronze screens to create a space reminiscent of a basilica.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The banking room can be entered from the 41st Street arch to the south; the 42nd Street arch to the north; the office building's vestibule to the northeast; and two doorways leading to the passenger- and freight-elevator lobbies to the west.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The floor slopes upward toward the south end of the room, since the 41st Street entrance is slightly higher than the entrance on 42nd Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Another ramp slopes upward toward the "Chapel" annex to the east.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The 42nd Street branch had a single waiting and banking room, obviating the need for clerks to frequently walk between back-room desks and public-facing counters.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The floor is made of polychrome marble, bordered by a cream-colored band of Traneville marble.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The floor is arranged in multicolored patterns, laid in asymmetrical panels to resemble throw rugs.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The patterns alternate between lozenges with stars, lozenges with squares, and hexagons.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A wooden staircase at the northeastern corner of the banking room leads to the basement; it contains Levanto marble walls and parapet, as well as wooden handrails.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The marble tellers' counter, 50 inches (130 cm) high, was in the middle of the banking room.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The high wainscot and counter base were made of Rosso Levanto marble.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A bronze teller's screen ran above the surface of the teller's counter.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] There were openings in the counter on its north and south sides.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The screen was capped by what *Architectural Forum* described as "21 squat immortal penny-savers in pierced levanto".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Behind the screen, and on the desks, were reflectors that illuminated the work space.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The east and west walls each have five arches supported by six polished-marble columns, each of a different color.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Proceeding from north to south, the columns are made of Rouge Jaspe, Alps Green, Campan Melange, Rouge Royal, Tinos Green, and Levanto marbles.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Each column measures 25 feet (7.6 m) high and has a diameter of 3 feet 2 inches (0.97 m).
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The columns' bases and capitals are made of Indiana limestone in high relief.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The arches were nearly completely filled with mosaic designs, except for stone grilles that concealed the openings for the heating system.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The remainder of the walls are made of stone in various types and textures.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Indiana limestone and Briar Hill and Buff Mountain sandstone are used for the main wall surfaces.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Marble, artificial stone, and plaster are also used.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The socle is made of Alps Green marble, and the walls above are made of limestone and sandstone.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Near the top of the wall, there was a deep-red frieze with white figures.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The ceiling above the banking room contains six deep beams, which are actually steel trusses.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] These beams are supported by imitation-stone corbels on the walls, which conceal steel brackets beneath.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The ceiling is coated with six layers of materials, giving the impression that it contains coffers and small wooden beams.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Six cast-bronze chandeliers are anchored from the ceiling, each of which has three tiers.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The central lamp was modeled after that of the Hagia Sophia.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Originally, the center of the ceiling had a skylight with twelve panels of pale amber glass.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The skylight measures 35 by 60 feet (11 by 18 m).
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The "Chapel" annex is located to the east of the banking room's northern section, connected via two large rectangular openings cut through the party wall on the eastern side of the banking room.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The design is similar to that of the banking room, with limestone and sandstone walls.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A second floor loggia overlooks the northern end of the annex's first floor, and below that is a set of double doors leading to the central arch of the arcade along 42nd Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] There are two chandeliers and a painted rhombus pattern on the flat ceiling.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A patterned frieze runs near the top of the wall.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The space to the west of the main banking room measures 20 feet (6.1 m) wide and 197.5 feet (60.2 m) long.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] It includes an entrance vestibule, as well as a lobby containing passenger and freight elevators.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The vestibule, located to the north and facing 42nd Street, contains a ceiling with three ceiling vaults.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] It includes a staircase to the New York City Subway's Grand Central–42nd Street station, serving the 4, 5, 6, <6>, 7, <7>, and S trains, along its western side.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] To the south is the elevator lobby, which contains decorative floor tiling and six painted ceiling vaults.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Six major trusses run perpendicular to the walls and are supported by twelve corbels, while smaller trusses run diagonally between alternating corbels.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Six chandeliers hang from the ceiling at the locations where the diagonal trusses cross each other.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The elevator doors contain bronze panels with various embossed motifs.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] In 1913, the Dual Contracts were signed by the Interborough Rapid Transit Company (IRT) and the Brooklyn–Manhattan Transit Corporation (BMT), two companies which operated parts of the present New York City Subway.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A set of platforms at Grand Central, now serving the IRT Lexington Avenue Line (4, 5, 6, and <6> trains), was to be built diagonally under the building site as part of the agreement.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] At the time, the site under the proposed station was occupied by Grand Union Hotel, which was condemned via eminent domain in February 1914.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The condemnation proceedings for the hotel cost $3.5 million (equal to $78.3 million in 2024).
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] To pay the station's construction cost, the Public Service Commission approved the construction of a 25-story building above the station.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] By May 1915, the building site had been excavated for the construction of the building.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Despite the passage of the 1916 Zoning Resolution, which required architectural setbacks to provide light to the streets below, the building plans conformed with the older zoning codes, which did not require setbacks.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Though the IRT Lexington Avenue Line's 42nd Street station opened in 1918, the site above the station was not developed as planned.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The Transit Commission attempted to sell the building site in May 1920 for $2.8 million (equal to $33.1 million in 2024), but no one placed a bid.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Then in July 1920, a realty consortium headed by investor Henry Mandel offered $2.9 million for the hotel (equal to $34.3 million in 2024), a proposal that was accepted.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The value of the land at the future building site was extremely valuable; by 1923, the *Rider's Guide to New York City* referred to the blocks of East 42nd Street between Park and Fifth Avenues as "Little Wall Street".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The Bowery Savings Bank, then located at 130 Bowery in lower Manhattan, was among the parties which were seeking to add an uptown location.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] In September 1920, its trustees unanimously agreed to look for an uptown site.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The trustees soon found a site on 42nd Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The bank's management were initially unenthusiastic about the 42nd Street site, because it was right next to the elevated Grand Central station.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] However, the bank's president pointed out that the original Bowery Savings Bank Building was itself next to an elevated line and that the 42nd Street location was very close to Grand Central Terminal and its attached subway station.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Another issue was that a standalone bank building at 42nd Street was too expensive, so the building would also have to contain offices.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The trustees bought the lot in November 1920 and established a committee the next month to draw up plans.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The Bowery Savings Bank's decision reflected the northward movement of commerce in Manhattan, as well as the influence of suburbs on new development in New York City's core.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] When the Bowery Savings Bank was planning its new uptown location, savings banks in New York were mostly limited to one location, a restriction that was not lifted until 1923.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] In November 1920, the bank circumvented this restriction by acquiring the Universal Savings Bank in lower Manhattan, which then relocated to 42nd Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The Bowery Savings Bank was the first bank in the state to take advantage of a special provision in the state law, which allowed a savings bank to operate two branches if it merged with another savings bank.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The Bowery Savings Bank took over the Universal Savings Bank in January 1921 and started operating a temporary branch next to Grand Central Terminal.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] That month, Mandel sold the Bowery Savings Bank the eastern half of the Grand Union Hotel site, which would be developed into an office building at 110 East 42nd Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] As per the purchase agreement between the bank and the corporation, the structures were to contain interlocking structures, including what was believed to be the city's tallest party wall separating two buildings.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] York and Sawyer, designers of several bank buildings in the eastern United States, had been hired to devise plans for the new Savings Bank at the site of the Grand Union Hotel.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The lead architect on the project was William Louis Ayres.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The plans were filed with the New York City Department of Buildings in April 1921.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Excavations had started in February 1921 in advance of the plans' approval, and that June, the building committee recommended to start construction immediately.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Construction on the building officially commenced that July with a groundbreaking ceremony.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] By the time the new branch opened in 1923, there were 155,000 people with accounts at the Bowery Savings Bank.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The bank had seen $1.5 million in deposits (equivalent to $28,344,727 in 2025) "on one day recently", compared to the $2,020 deposited on the original branch's opening day in 1834 (equivalent to $65,145 in 2025).
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The 42nd Street branch's managers referred to the location as the "42nd Street Office of the Bowery Savings Bank", refusing to call it a "branch".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The bank's 42nd Street branch opened on June 25, 1923, with 5,600 accounts, more than half of which had been transferred from the Universal Savings branch.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Just prior to the branch's opening, the bank moved $202 million of deposits (equal to $2.9 billion in 2024) the original branch to the new branch, using 14 armored cars guarded by 100 heavily armed policemen.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The bank retained its original offices on Bowery.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Upon the opening of 110 East 42nd Street, the branch had total deposits of $177 million (equal to $2.5 billion in 2024).
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] There were 2,500 new accounts opened at the 42nd Street branch on the first day of operation.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Customers registered 33,803 new accounts in the following nine months, and total deposits at the 42nd Street branch increased by $25 million in that time period (equal to $357.3 million in 2024).
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The presence of the new Bowery Savings Bank branch and of brokerage firms on 42nd Street bolstered its reputation as a "Little Wall Street".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Some alterations were made to the main building in 1927, including the installation of a clock, bronze display cases, and revolving doors outside the 42nd Street entrance.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The bank established a safe-deposit department at its 42nd Street branch in March 1929, with 2,924 safe-deposit boxes in seven sizes.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] By the end of that year, the bank had installed 860 more safe-deposit boxes to address growing demand.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A six-story addition to the east, which came to be called "The Chapel", was proposed in March 1931.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] York and Sawyer filed plans for the annex that August.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The first floor of the annex would contain offices for administration, collection, information, a nd new accounts.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The second story would include mortgage offices; the third story would be for the controller's department; and the fourth story would include service rooms.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Louis Ayres designed the addition, while Marc Eidlitz & Son, Inc. erected the structure.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The fifth floor facade's marble colonnettes were replaced with granite ones in 1951, and the annex's windows and entrance were redesigned in 1956.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A plaque was erected outside 110 East 42nd Street in 1957, designating it as a point of interest and an unofficial "landmark".
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The screen above the 42nd Street archway were replaced with a glass window in 1962.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission (LPC) first considered designating the Bowery Savings Bank branch at 110 East 42nd Street as a landmark in 1966.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A year after the Bowery Savings Bank was acquired by H.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Ahmanson & Co. in 1991, the building's ownership was jointly transferred to Ahmanson and a limited partnership, which owned the building as a condominium.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The LPC hosted public hearings in 1993 to determine whether to designate the Bowery Savings Bank branch at 110 East 42nd Street, as well as the interior of the 130 Grand Street branch, as city landmarks.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Greenpoint Bank took over the banking spaces in 1995, after having bought many of Ahmanson's branches.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] 110 East 42nd Street's facade and interior were designated as city landmarks in 1996.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] SL Green bought the building in March 1998 and subsequently renovated the lobby as well as replaced the elevators.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The ground-floor banking room was converted to a Cipriani restaurant and upscale event space, with Cipriani finalizing the deal for the new location in January 1999.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] At the same time, with the renovation and revival of Grand Central in the late 1990s, large tenants began occupying 110 East 42nd's office space.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] In 2007, Gotham Realty Holdings bought the building for $111.5 million, funding the purchase with a loan of $124 million from Carlton Advisory Services.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] By 2011, Gotham was unable to pay the remaining $90 million of its loan.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] In an attempt to avoid foreclosure, the loan servicer split the loan into a $65 million interest-payable note and a $25 million interest-free note.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] This failed and SL Green took back the property in 2011, paying $85.5 million.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] SL Green also bought the building's garage in 2013.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] By 2014, the building was completely occupied by tenants such as The Princeton Review, Metro-North Railroad, and Morgan, Lewis & Bockius.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] At the time, the restrooms and corridors on the office floors had just been upgraded.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The areas immediately surrounding Grand Central, including 110 East 42nd, had 1.8 million square feet (170,000 m2) of air rights above the terminal and its rail yards.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] This allowed for the construction of developments with that maximum floor area above Grand Central.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] That year, some of 110 East 42nd's unused air rights were passed to One Vanderbilt, a 1,401-foot-tall (427 m) skyscraper being built a block to the west.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] In May 2020, amid a loss of income during the COVID-19 pandemic in New York City, Cipriani defaulted on a mortgage loan that had been placed on its event venues at 110 East 42nd Street and 55 Wall Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] A special servicer took over the mortgage in 2021, but the two event venues were at risk of foreclosure by the end of that year.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] In December 2021, SL Green sold the building's 6th to 18th floors, as well as the building's garage, to Meadow Partners for $117 million.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Meadow obtained $58.5 million from Apollo Global Management to finance the acquisition.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] By June 2022, King Street Capital Management was considering giving Cipriani $150 million to refinance the debt on 110 East 42nd Street and 55 Wall Street.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Carey gave Cipriani a $52.1 million commercial mortgage-backed securities loan and a $28 million mezzanine loan for the two properties.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Shortly after the building was completed, Charles G.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The fifth edition of the *AIA Guide to New York City* referred to 110 East 42nd Street as "one of the great spaces of New York." A 1986 article in the Canadian newspaper *The Globe and Mail* said that 110 East 42nd Street "flaunts the power of New York money.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Stupendously lavish, marbled and pillared and bronzed and tiled, it still has elegant Art Deco banking tables where you can write out cheques with an Art Deco ballpoint." Robert A.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] Stern wrote that the Bowery Savings Bank's midtown building "was without question the era's most opulent bank" and that it "rivaled" the original branch as the city's most ornate bank building.
[src:2-park-avenue/110-east-42nd-street] The building's design was not widely copied by other bank buildings in New York City, but its use of a variety of architectural elements was nonetheless emulated in other banks' designs.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The facade of the first three stories is made of stone and largely contains storefronts, except for a central entrance on Park Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The lower section of the building occupies nearly its entire lot, and the building contains setbacks at the 11th, 18th, and 25th stories.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The facade contains a polychrome color scheme above the 16th floor, including colored terracotta tiles manufactured by Léon-Victor Solon.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The design of the vaulted main lobby dates to the 1970s, when decorations such as a mural by Winold Reiss were added.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Office tenants over the years have included the Boy Scouts of America, as well as various textiles, clothing, media, and financial firms.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The site had been occupied by the Park Avenue Hotel since the 1870s.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Developer Henry Mandel bought the hotel in 1925 in conjunction with a nearby development; he sold the site to Adelson, who erected the building and issued bonds to fund the project.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The Continental Bank and Trust Company took over the building in foreclosure in 1935, and real-estate firm Webb and Knapp acquired it in 1953.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] After several sales in the 1960s, Sheldon Lewis Breitbart bought 2 Park Avenue's leasehold in 1962.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Breitbart renovated the lobby after buying the building outright in 1976.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Mendik acquired the building in 1986 after several of the building's limited partners accused Breitbart of impropriety.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Mendik merged his company in 1997 with Vornado Realty Trust, which sold the building in 2003 to a German firm.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Morgan Stanley Real Estate bought a majority stake in 2 Park Avenue in 2007 and sold it to Haddad Brands in 2024.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] 2 Park Avenue occupies the eastern section of a city block in the Murray Hill neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] It is bounded by 32nd Street on the south, Park Avenue on the east, and 33rd Street on the north; the city block extends westward to Madison Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The building's land lot has a total area of 40,500 sq ft (3,760 m2).
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] It measures 197.5 ft (60.2 m) from north to south and 205 ft (62 m) from west to east.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Entrances to the New York City Subway's 33rd Street station are directly outside the building's northeast and southeast corners.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The building is on the same block as 29 East 32nd Street to the west.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Other nearby buildings include the Hotel Grand Union to the southwest, Madison Belmont Building to the northwest, 4 Park Avenue to the north, and 3 Park Avenue to the northeast.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The adjacent portion of Park Avenue slopes upward from south to north.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The site was part of the 18th-century estate of merchant Robert Murray.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In the 1860s, after the Park Avenue Tunnel was built, the segment of Fourth Avenue between 34th and 40th Streets was renamed Park Avenue, while the avenue's name south of 34th Street remained unchanged.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Fourth and Park Avenues in Murray Hill had been developed with upscale residences by the 1870s.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The site had previously been occupied by the Park Avenue Hotel, which was built in 1878 by dry-goods businessman Alexander Turney Stewart and was originally a hotel for "working girls".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] This building was seven or eight stories high, with 502 rooms, and had an internal courtyard.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Despite being destroyed in a 1902 fire that killed 17 people, the hotel was rebuilt and continued to operate for two decades.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] *The New York Times* described the hotel as "one of the most popular hostelries in New York City" when it was in operation.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] 2 Park Avenue was designed by Ely Jacques Kahn in the Art Deco style.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] It rises 28 or 29 stories and measures about 350 ft (110 m) to its roof.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The lower section of the building occupies nearly its entire lot, but there is a light court facing west toward the adjacent building.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On the western side of the building, there is a setback along 32nd and 33rd Street on the 11th story.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] There is a setback on all sides at the 18th story, above the tops of the western wings.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The building has another setback at the 26th story; the top three stories are treated as a penthouse.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The building's height was intended to maximize profit; since elevators and other service areas took up a significant part of the rentable area on upper stories, it would have been unprofitable to build a taller structure.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The western elevation of the facade, on Park Avenue, is divided into nine bays along each of the 1st through 17th stories and seven bays on each of the 18th through 25th stories.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Generally, the two outermost bays are designed similarly to each other, and the central bays share a common design that contrasts with the outer bays.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The northern and southern elevations are each divided into ten bays along each of the 1st through 17th stories.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The easternmost seven bays are divided into two outer bays and five central bays (similar in design to the facade on Park Avenue), while the westernmost three bays are again different in design.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] These taper to six bays on the 18th through 25th stories.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The facade contains a polychrome color scheme above the 16th floor, which Kahn said was inspired by the texture of fabric.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Kahn's friend Léon-Victor Solon designed the polychrome terracotta panels.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] These consisted of red, yellow, green, and blue panels with glazing, and black panels with a luster finish.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] According to Kahn's biographer Jewel Stern, Solon had been selected because he was "the nation's leading authority on architectural polychromy".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] At the time of the building's completion, few buildings used colored terracotta panels on facades, though such panels were characteristic of Kahn's work during the 1920s.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Kahn had wanted to include decorative forms in the building's design, but typical sculpted ornamentation was difficult to see from the street.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Unlike traditional decorations (which were applied to a completed curtain wall) the terracotta panels on 2 Park Avenue's facade are part of the curtain wall itself.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The main entrance is recessed within the central bay.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The floors of the vestibule are paved in travertine.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The main entrance to the lobby consists of two revolving bronze doors flanked by single bronze doors; all are decorated with geometric motifs.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Above these is an ornate bronze transom bar, as well as a semicircular window.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The transom contains motifs relating to machines, designed in a style resembling Frank Lloyd Wright's work.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The mosaic ceiling was intended to evoke the design of a tapestry, with blue, black, and red tesserae as well as gold accents.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The walls on either side are made of polished gray marble and originally contained light sconces.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The side walls each contain a bronze door with an illuminated sign above it.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The south wall also has a bronze tenant directory and the north wall contains a second door leading to the storefronts.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] At the bottom of the 1st story is a water table made of granite.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The 1st through 3rd stories are clad with tan stone, which blends in with the brick on the upper stories.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The 1st and 2nd stories contain double-height openings, divided by vertical stone piers.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The 1st story includes storefronts made of metal and glass, above which are horizontal spandrels made of cast iron.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Panels were installed in front of these spandrels at some point in the 20th century before being removed.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Each 2nd-story window is composed of a large central window between a pair of smaller sash windows, except in the central bay on Park Avenue, which contains four sash windows separated by triangular piers.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] There is a cyma reversa molding above these windows.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On the 3rd story, the outermost two bays each contain two sash windows.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The central bays are separated from each other by wide triangular piers; each bay has four narrow sash windows separated by flat pilasters.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The lowest three stories on Park Avenue, 32nd Street, and 33rd Street are similar, with minor exceptions.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On 33rd Street, there is a secondary entrance in the fifth bay from east, with bronze and glass doors.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] An unused service entrance is placed on 32nd Street as well.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The westernmost two bays on 32nd Street contain vehicular loading docks with roller shutters.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On all three elevations, at the 4th through 15th stories, each of the outer bays has two rectangular windows per floor, which are separated by flat pilasters.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The flat brick surfaces of the outer bays contrast with the central bays' textured surfaces.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Furthermore, the bricks in the outer bays are lighter in tone than with the bricks in the central bays, providing more visual contrast.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On all three elevations, each of the central bays contains four windows on each floor.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The windows of each bay are separated vertically by narrow brick pilasters and horizontally by darker-brick spandrels, which are textured to resemble woven fabric.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The spandrels alternately contain narrow brick headers, which project from the wall, and wider brick stretchers, which are flush with the wall.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Furthermore, each four-window bay is separated by triangular brick piers, which are supported by stone corbels on the 3rd story and rise to the 17th story.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] At the setbacks, the brick piers are topped by blue terracotta panels.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On the north and south elevations, the westernmost three bays are also faced with brick and divided by triangular piers, but there are only three windows per bay.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Between the 16th story and the roof are polychrome terracotta panels, designed with several geometric and abstract motifs.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In the center bays, the spandrels above the 15th and 16th stories contain superimposed geometric motifs in red, yellow, green, and blue.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The panels above the 17th story are treated as an attic section, with different designs above the central and outer bays.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The central windows are topped by projecting yellow bars, while the brick piers are topped by blue terracotta.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In the outermost bays, the 16th- and 17th-story windows are interspersed with horizontal bands of orange and yellow.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Above the 17th story, the outer bays contain red, blue, and black bands (from bottom to top), each with vertical yellow bars.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The outer panels above the 17th story contain curving shapes, the only curved motifs used in any of the terracotta panels.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Above the 18th to 22nd stories, there is a blue-on-yellow spandrel above each of the windows in the central bays.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The outer bays contain horizontal orange-and-yellow bands between the windows on each story.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The spandrels between the 24th and 25th stories contain geometric motifs in red, yellow, green, and blue, while the windows in the outer bays are interspersed with horizontal bands of orange and yellow.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Above the 25th story, the central and outer bays are topped by ornament similar to that above the 17th story.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The main difference is that the outer bays contain incisions above the 25th story.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The top three stories are decorated similarly to the 16th and 17th and the 24th and 25th floors, except that the outer bays also have colored terracotta.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The main entrance to the building is from Park Avenue, though the building also has entrances from 32nd and 33rd Streets, all connected via passageways.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] There was also an entrance from the subway station in the basement.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The lobby's design largely consisted of bronze, marble, and mosaic tiles, arranged in overlaid geometric motifs.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The passageway from Park Avenue contained travertine floors.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Each of the walls consisted of a tall gray-marble wainscoting, above which was a gilded plaster frieze with motifs such as plants, chevrons, volutes, prisms, and column shapes.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Octagonal bronze-and-glass chandeliers, with cantilevered glass panels, were initially suspended from the ceiling via metal rods.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The Park Avenue lobby intersects a vaulted north–south passageway connecting 32nd and 33rd Streets.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The north–south passageway originally had multi-tiered chandeliers, each containing eight bronze pendants.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The north–south passageway contained an arch leading back to Park Avenue, which was topped by a colorful tympanum.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The lights, mailbox, and radiator grilles were decorated similarly to the rest of the lobby.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In the 1950s, many of these decorations were replaced, while the ceiling was painted white.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] During a renovation in the 1970s, a Winold Reiss mural of New York City's skyline and Sabino glass chandeliers were added to the lobby.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The mural came from a Longchamps restaurant at 59th Street and Madison Avenue, while the chandeliers came from a Simpsons department store in Toronto, Ontario.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Originally, there were also nine storefronts at ground level.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Below street level are freight and loading platforms.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Above the 17th-story setback, each of the floors are 22,500 ft2 (2,090 m2).
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Though 2 Park Avenue could accommodate both offices and showrooms, its developers also wanted the ability to lease the space to manufacturers if there were not enough office or showroom tenants.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] At the time of the building's construction, up to 25 percent of the space could be used for manufacturing.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Consequently, 2 Park Avenue's floor slabs contained a high floor–load capacity, and it also included freight elevators and other services.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] At ground level, the elevators are clustered where the passageways from each entrance intersect.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On the remaining stories, there are mechanical rooms surrounding each elevator bank.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The superstructure used 10,000 short tons (8,900 long tons; 9,100 t) of steel.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The 1st through 17th stories are divided by piers, which are spaced 21 to 22 feet (6.4 to 6.7 m) apart at their centers; at the rear of each story, the piers are spaced more closely.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The ceilings measured 12 feet (3.7 m) high, providing large work spaces for industrial tenants.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The work spaces above the 17th story were generally shallower, accommodating office tenants.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On the 20th floor is a business center with a coworking space, 74 offices, and meeting rooms.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The developer Henry Mandel acquired the lots on the eastern side of Fourth Avenue between 32nd and 33rd Street in 1923 under the name "One Park Avenue Corporation".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] He intended to erect an office building on the site.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Since the house numbering system reset at the southern end of Park Avenue, buildings between 32nd and 34th Streets originally had Fourth Avenue addresses.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Park Avenue was extended southward from 34th to 32nd Street in 1924, but controversies over the renaming continued until 1930.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The site of the Park Avenue Hotel had long been difficult to redevelop because it faced a streetcar depot across Park Avenue, which was demolished to make way for 1 Park Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Mandel bought the old Park Avenue Hotel in May 1925, with plans to build 2 Park Avenue, a 35-story office building, on the site.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] He immediately started planning for the new development, even though the hotel continued to operate under a lease that did not expire until 1927.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Mandel wanted to connect 1 and 2 Park Avenue via an underpass that also provided access to the subway.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The Park Avenue Hotel site was sold again in April 1926, this time to Abe N.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Adelson, who formed the Two Park Avenue Corporation to develop the building.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] That September, the Park Avenue Hotel closed and all its furnishings were sold off.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Ely Jacques Kahn was hired to develop alternative plans for an industrial building or an office building, since the owners did not know what to develop on the site.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Kahn's firm Buchman and Kahn created four separate sketches of the building in four months.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The first sketch, scheme A, called for a base with multiple setbacks and a central tower with a pyramidal roof.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Scheme B was a variation of scheme A with diagonal corners and without a pyramidal roof.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Schemes C and D also depicted a central tower above a base with multiple setbacks, but the setbacks in scheme D were simpler than those in scheme C.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The final plans called for a much simpler massing without a tower.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Buchman and Kahn filed plans for a building at 2 Park Avenue, to cost $4 million, in October 1926.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The structure was to be designed in the Art Deco style, making it one of the first office buildings in Manhattan to be designed in that style.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] To maximize usable space, Kahn designed the structure as a nearly square block with large floor areas and a light court in the rear.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Solon and Kahn created mockups of the facade's terracotta panels using plaster and cardboard boxes.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The Federal Terra Cotta Company then created full-sized mockups of the panels to see how they looked from 250 feet (76 m) away.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Though Adelson doubted the effectiveness of these designs, consulting architect Raymond Hood reassured the developer of Kahn's expertise.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Halley, Knox & Koenig provided a $1.25 million mortgage on the site in December 1926.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Straus & Co. provided $9 million in permanent financing including a $6.5 million first mortgage.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Straus had also tried to convince Kahn to tone down the colorful design, but Kahn replied that his panels would be less expensive than traditional sculptured decoration.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Straus established the Park Avenue and 33rd Street Corporation, which would issue $6.5 million in sinking fund bonds, secured by the land and building.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Steel contractors Shroder & Koppel began erecting the steel superstructure at the end of March 1927, at which point over one-fifth of the building was leased.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] That July, the New York Building Congress gave craftsmanship awards to many workers who were involved in construction.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] By November 1927, the building was nearly fully leased.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Two months later, the Two Park Avenue Corporation hosted a dinner in which it presented a ceremonial cup to Adelson, honoring his involvement in the building's development.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] When the building was completed, its storefronts were occupied by Seward National Bank, Block, Maloney & Co., and the Bloomsburg Silk Mill.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Several dry goods and textiles merchants occupied the lower floors, including Mills & Gibb.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Among the largest tenants were Peierle, Buhler & Co. and Robert Reis & Co., which each occupied three full floors.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] On the 17th floor were the national headquarters of the Boy Scouts of America.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Occupants of the 18th through 25th stories included the United States Leather Company, the Building Trades Employers' Association, and advertising firm Gardiner & Wells.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The Building Trades Employers' Association, which occupied the entire 25th floor, sought to name the building the "New York Builders' Exchange".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The top two floors were the offices of Buchman & Kahn, the building's own architects.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The Tammany Hall political organization also temporarily leased space at 2 Park Avenue while its permanent home at 44 Union Square was being completed.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The Straus National Bank and Trust Company placed a $2.5 million second mortgage on the property in July 1929.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] At the time, the building's brokers cited 2 Park Avenue as being fully rented.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The same year, real-estate developer Robert W.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Phillips cited 2 Park Avenue as one of several successful tall buildings that had been recently developed.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Among the building's tenants in the early 1930s were the Royal Typewriter Company, the Metropolitan Life Insurance Company, shirt manufacturer Cluett Peabody & Company, several leather companies, and several handkerchief manufacturers.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] By February 1934, the Continental Bank and Trust Company sought to foreclose on the $6.5 million first mortgage from S.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] At the time, 8,000 individuals owned $8.175 million in outstanding bonds on the building, over two-thirds of which agreed on a reorganization plan.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The building was auctioned in August 1934 and Continental took over the building that month.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In the nine months after the reorganization, 2 Park Avenue had $225,000 in net profit.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Hunter College officials leased three and a half floors at 2 Park Avenue in February 1936, after Hunter's existing building burned down, and the college added several classrooms and study halls to the space within three weeks.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Hunter continued to lease space at 2 Park Avenue for several years.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Other tenants during the 1940s included the Bibb Manufacturing Company, the Home Owners' Loan Corporation, the United States Mission to the United Nations, and a regional office of the National Labor Relations Board.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In particular, the United Nations mission's presence led *The New York Times* to characterize 2 Park Avenue as "our global embassy on Park Avenue".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In 1947, Two Park Avenue Building Inc. refinanced the building with a $4.76 million mortgage, replacing the original first mortgage.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Bankers Trust leased some space in the 1950s, as did the Free Europe Committee.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Real-estate firm Webb and Knapp acquired control of 2 Park Avenue in April 1953, paying off a $2.7 million mortgage.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] That November, the Connecticut Life Insurance Company provided a $6.75 million mortgage loan for 2 Park Avenue to Webb and Knapp.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] During the 1950s, the building was 98 percent occupied by companies in a variety of trades.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] These included the Boy Scouts, the Blue Shield Association, Chase Manhattan Bank, the Empire City Savings Bank, the Federal Housing Administration, Phoenix Mutual Life Insurance, and Radio Free Europe.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The law firm of Herrick Feinstein also leased some space in 1957 and stayed for over half a century, while publisher W.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Over a five-year period in the late 1950s and early 1960s, the building underwent a $3 million renovation, which included automating 16 manually operated elevators.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] By 1960, Webb and Knapp was struggling financially and had sold off a partial ownership stake in 2 Park Avenue and several of its other buildings.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] William Zeckendorf, the chairman of Webb and Knapp, subsequently testified that the building was sold in June 1959 to Chicago businessman Henry Crown, with a caveat that Zeckendorf had to buy it back if certain criteria were met.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Crown asked Zeckendorf to buy back the building in January 1961, and Zeckendorf hired Samuel Lemberg to buy 2 Park Avenue, which Lemberg then sold to Joseph Lubin.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In June 1962, Sheldon Lewis Breitbart of the Breitbart Corporation bought 2 Park Avenue's leasehold from a limited partnership, Two Park Avenue Company.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The next month, Breitbart sold the leasehold for $8.35 million back to Two Park Avenue Company.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] One of Zeckendorf's trustees, Mortimer M.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Caplin, sued Zeckendorf in 1967, alleging the transactions were part of a trend of mismanagement.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Caplin dropped his complaints against the 2 Park Avenue transactions in 1972 in return for a $35,000 settlement.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Breitbart bought the land and building outright in 1976, paying $4 million to Ann L.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The next year, Breitbart hired Kwan Lau and Beverly Birks to renovate the lobby with Art Deco decorations that were popular in the mid-20th century.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] During that decade, 2 Park Avenue's tenants included publisher E.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Dutton, the editorial offices of *Harper's Magazine*, and the offices of *Esquire* magazine.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In addition, the building's retail tenants included French restaurant La Coupole.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Bandler secretly bought a share in the building's ownership in 1982 after Breitbart had refused to allow Bandler's associate, Julien Studley, buy an ownership stake.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Bandler and Studley bought more shares in 2 Park Avenue over the next two years, but Breitbart also refused to acknowledge that the men were partial owners.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In an attempt to gain total ownership of the building, Bandler and Studley convinced some of the building's 1,040 limited partners to file a class action lawsuit against Breitbart, on the basis that he had paid "unauthorized and excessive management fees" to himself and to his wife Barbara.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The New York Supreme Court ruled in Breitbart's favor, but acting Court of Appeals justice Francis Pecora reversed the Supreme Court's decision.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The appeals court ruled that Breitbart had to pay $6 million in damages, forced Breitbart to resign as the building's general partner, and appointed John Bower as a receiver to sell the property.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Bandler alleged that Breitbart should not be allowed to sell 2 Park Avenue unless Breitbart recognized Bandler's ownership stake.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Bower hired the Williams Real Estate Company, which recommended that the building be sold immediately so the limited partners could receive capital gains tax relief.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The building was sold at auction in December 1986 to a syndicate of Bernard Mendik and EF Hutton for $151 million.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Despite not providing documentation for his work, Bower was paid $7.7 million for his role in the receivership proceedings, or about $4,000 an hour.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] This was about 70 times higher than the next-largest payment for a receivership proceeding in New York state.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] This represented five percent of the total sale price, the maximum allowed under state law.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Breitbart appealed the award in February 1988, prompting the weekly newspaper *Manhattan Lawyer* to publish three articles about the transaction.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The state appellate division vacated Bower's fee that June, but Pecora restored it that August without holding a hearing.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] After another appeal in December 1988, the appellate division reduced the payment to $5 million, citing the "complex nature and extremely high quality of the service rendered"; this was still 40 times higher than the next-largest payment to a receiver in New York.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In the 1990s, the building contained the headquarters of *New York Newsday*, the New York City edition of Long Island daily newspaper *Newsday*.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The American Place restaurant also opened in the building at that time.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Despite the early-1990s economic downturn, 2 Park Avenue and Mendik's other properties remained over 95 percent occupied because of what *Crain's New York* described as Mendik's "reputation for quality management".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In 1996, Mendik announced that he would form a real estate investment trust to control seven of his properties in Midtown Manhattan, including 2 Park Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] This move would allow Mendik to raise up to $220 million.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The next year, Mendik announced his company would merge with Steven Roth's Vornado Realty Trust, giving Vornado control of 2 Park Avenue and Mendik's other properties.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] By the late 1990s, the neighborhood was a hub for publishing companies, and Matthew Bender & Company and Times Mirror Company occupied 2 Park Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] A branch of cheese restaurant Artisanal opened in the building in 2001, and Hartford Financial Services moved to the building that year after being displaced in the September 11 attacks.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Vornado placed the building for sale in May 2003; at the time, it was 99 percent leased.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] That August, German firm SEB Immobililien-Investment GmbH agreed to buy the building for $157 million.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Its tenants at the time included the Tribune Company (succeeded by the Bonnier Corporation), Simplicity Pattern, The New York Community Trust, and United Way of New York City.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Several tenants also leased space in the mid-2000s, including life-insurance company Penn Mutual and fragrance company Coty Inc.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission (LPC) designated 2 Park Avenue and the nearby 404 Fifth Avenue as official city landmarks on April 18, 2006.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] L&L Holding and General Electric Pension Trust bought 2 Park Avenue the same year for $450 million and refinanced the building in an all-cash transaction.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Morgan Stanley Real Estate paid $519 million for a majority stake in the building in early 2007.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Cushman & Wakefield took over leasing at the building in 2010.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Among the major office tenants in the early 2010s were fashion firm Kate Spade New York as well as British Airways, the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, the North Shore-LIJ Health System, and Gilt Groupe.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The building's commercial tenants included Europa Café, Crumbs Bake Shop, and Pret a Manger, which faced competition from food trucks on Park Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The building's manager requested in 2011 that the New York City Department of Transportation create a no-idling zone outside 2 Park Avenue; he claimed that food-truck owners had caused thousands of dollars in damage, resulting in complaints from tenants.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] By 2014, the building was fully leased after clothing company Talbots leased some retail space.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Other tenants in the mid-2010s included textiles firm Delta Galil Industries and technology firm The Trade Desk.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] In 2024, Haddad Brands agreed to pay Morgan Stanley about $360 million for 2 Park Avenue.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The sale, coming at a time when many office buildings in the U.S. were being sold at discounted rates, came at a 31% discount from the price that Morgan Stanley had paid in 2007.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] After Haddad Brands bought the building, it leased space to multiple firms, including Via Transportation and the City University of New York.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] By mid-2026, the building was nearly fully leased.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Of all buildings that Ely Jacques Kahn designed, 2 Park Avenue received the most attention from architectural critics.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Near the building's completion, Solon brought Michael A.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Mikkelson of *Architectural Record*, to see the building.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Mikkelson thought the building began "a new chapter in the history of sky-scraper design".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The visit also prompted Mikkelson to publish a 22-page "Portfolio of Current Architecture" in April 1928, featuring 2 Park Avenue exclusively.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] When the building was completed, architectural critic Lewis Mumford praised the building's facade, massing, and interior, in spite of his general disdain toward skyscrapers.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Mumford said the form and facade combined to create "the boldest and clearest note among all our recent achievements in skyscraper architecture".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] *Architectural Record* described the building's lobby as "probably the most impressive in the country".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] The photographer Cervin Robinson took an image of 2 Park Avenue, with the Empire State Building behind it, for his 1975 book *Skyscraper Style: Art Deco New York*.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] This led Paul Goldberger of *The New York Times* to describe the scene as one of several that "deserve to become classics".
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] When the building's lobby was renovated in 1977, Goldberger wrote: "It is all bright, shiny and full of enthusiasm for Art Deco", criticizing only the blue ceiling.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Robins described 2 Park Avenue as containing one of the "most striking Art Deco facades" in New York City.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] According to writers Jewel Stern and John A.
[src:2-park-avenue/2-park-avenue] Stuart, 2 Park Avenue was "the project that confirmed Kahn's reputation as a modernist".
